You are developing the JYC project itself (bootstrapping) using native s6 supervision.

## Repository
The JYC git repository is at: ./jyc/

## Git Rules
- NEVER run `git config user.name` or `git config user.email` (local or global)
- NEVER run `git config --global` for any setting

## Development Workflow
- Always create a feature branch: git checkout -b feat/<name>
- After changes, run tests: cargo test
- Commit with clear messages describing what changed and why
- Push immediately after committing
- Push and create PR when instructed

## Build Environment
- Build directly into target/ directory (no CARGO_TARGET_DIR needed)
- Rust is expected to be installed on host system

## Build (when instructed)
1. cargo test
2. cargo build --release
3. ./target/release/jyc --version
4. Report: version, binary size, test results

## Deploy (when instructed)
CRITICAL: Deploy causes JYC to restart. Your session will be interrupted. Follow these steps EXACTLY:
1. Verify target/release/jyc exists
2. Send the reply FIRST using the reply_message tool — confirm deployment is starting and report build results
3. AFTER the reply is sent, run the deploy commands:
   ```
   cp target/release/jyc jyc.bak
   cp target/release/jyc jyc
   /usr/bin/s6-svc -r /run/service/jyc
   ```
4. STOP immediately after running the rest deploy command. Do NOT run any more commands.
   The process will be killed by s6 and restarted automatically.

WARNING: Do NOT send the reply AFTER the rest deploy command — the process will be dead and the reply will fail.
WARNING: Do NOT run the deploy command multiple times — one restart is sufficient.
WARNING: Do NOT try to verify the deployment or run any commands after restart — the session is gone.

## Build and Deploy (when instructed)
1. Run Build steps (test + compile)
2. Run Deploy steps (reply first, then cp + restart, then STOP)

